<HEADLINE>
<P>
USX'S INCOME DROPS 7% TO $163 MILLION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Reuters 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
PITTSBURGH 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
USX Corp. said Tuesday that it will transfer control of its steel division to a 
wholly owned subsidiary, a move seen by analysts as paving the way for the 
once-mighty steel company to move out of the business altogether. 
</P>
<P>
Separately, on Tuesday the Pittsburgh-based conglomerate also reported lower 
third-quarter profit. 
</P>
<P>
The company said it had net income in the July to September period of $163 
million, down 7% from a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
But operating income -- net income minus special charges -- rose 25% to $382 
million. Sales also rose 16%, to $5.1 billion. 
</P>
<P>
The company's energy business had operating income of $238 million on sales of 
$3.7 billion, compared to $189 million on sales of $3 billion a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
The steel segment had operating income of $63 million on sales of $1.3 billion, 
down from $85 million on the same sales in the third quarter of 1989. 
</P>
<P>
USX -- formerly U.S. Steel Corp. but now a diversified manufacturer heavily 
involved in the energy business -- said its board of directors approved 
spinning off the steel-producing USS division into a separate company. 
</P>
<P>
The move "will provide flexibility for any steel restructuring undertaken by 
the firm," said USX Chairman Charles Corry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
