<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: HUNTINGTON BEACH; 
</P>
<P>
SKINHEADS TO RALLY FOR METZGER AT PARK 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By BILL BILLITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
City officials on Tuesday confirmed that a group of skinheads supporting race 
separatist Tom Metzger are expected to meet Saturday in Central Park. 
</P>
<P>
"As long as the group is not over 25 persons, we can't prohibit them from 
meeting in the park," Mayor Thomas J. Mays said. He said that about 20 to 25 
people are expected to show up. 
</P>
<P>
The rally, by self-avowed skinheads, is to show support for Metzger in the wake 
of hisloss of a civil court case in Portland, Ore. In that case, which was 
decided last week by a jury, Metzger and his organization, White Aryan 
Resistance, was ordered to pay $12.5 million in damages to the family of a 
black man killed by followers of that organization. 
</P>
<P>
The city first heard of the proposed rally from an anonymous caller who sought 
information about use of Central Park. The caller said skinheads wanted to have 
a rally for Metzger. 
</P>
<P>
Later, a permit request was filed, asking for use of the park with sound 
amplification equipment. The city denied the sound amplification request but 
could not legally deny park access to the group as long as it does not exceed 
25, Mays said. Groups larger than that require extra city services and thus 
require permits, he noted. 
</P>
<P>
Police Chief Ronald E. Lowenberg said officers will be on hand at the park. 
</P>
<P>
"I have some concerns about that type of group coming to our park and what 
other type groups they may draw," Lowenberg said. "The potential for conflict 
is significant. And so we hope nobody shows up. But from a proactive point of 
view, we have to be prepared. We will be keeping our eye on the area." 
</P>
<P>
Mays said he hopes that people, including opponents of Metzger, will not come 
to the park Saturday to see the rally. He said that an influx of curiosity 
seekers or opponents of Metzger would only "add to their (the skinheads') crowd 
and thus add to the attention they want to get." 
</P>
<P>
Mays said that he deplores the race separation sentiments of Metzger's 
followers but conceded that they have the constitutional right to meet and 
speak. BILL BILLITER 
</P>
</TEXT>
