<HEADLINE>
<P>
METRO DIGEST / LOCAL NEWS IN BRIEF: EX-TEACHER GETS PROBATION IN ABUSE OF 5 
STUDENTS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A former special education teacher convicted of verbally and physically abusing 
five seriously handicapped students at a San Pedro school was sentenced this 
week to two years' probation and ordered to undergo counseling. 
</P>
<P>
San Pedro Municipal Court Judge Lois Anderson Smaltz also ordered Juanita 
Barnett, 59, to perform 200 hours of community service and barred her from 
working with children under age 13. 
</P>
<P>
Barnett was convicted in August on five counts of willful cruelty toward a 
child. A jury found that she had threatened children in her class at Willenberg 
Special Education Center and struck them with her hands, a hairbrush and a 
jigsaw puzzle, said Deputy Dist. Atty. Juana Webman. 
</P>
<P>
Smaltz said overwhelming support from the community and Barnett's 26-year 
record of service made her conclude that the abuse was aberrant behavior by a 
"a lady who cares very much about children." 
</P>
</TEXT>
