<HEADLINE>
<P>
VENTURA COUNTY NEWS ROUNDUP: SIMI VALLEY; 
</P>
<P>
DAVIS OKS RELEASE OF POLICE OFFICER FILE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CARLOS V. LOZANO 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Ventura County supervisorial candidate Bill Davis announced Tuesday that he 
will authorize release of his service record as a Culver City police officer to 
satisfy questions raised by opponent Vicky Howard. 
</P>
<P>
Howard, who serves on the Simi Valley City Council with Davis, has criticized 
her opponent for not allowing his police personnel file to be released. 
</P>
<P>
Davis first refused to authorize release of his police record, saying "there 
are things there that I don't think are anybody's business." 
</P>
<P>
But Davis said Tuesday that he changed his mind because he wanted to put to 
rest any doubts that he was, in fact, a police officer at one time. 
</P>
<P>
Davis has said he served as a Culver City police officer for seven months more 
than 40 years ago. He said he resigned after witnessing the death of a child 
who had been hit by a car. CARLOS V. LOZANO 
</P>
</TEXT>
